{"title":"Open-Vocabulary Camouflaged Object Segmentation","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Open-vocabulary dense prediction benchmarks are not tailored to imperceptible, camouflaged objects, making it hard to evaluate models’ ability to generalize to unseen classes in complex scenes.","method":"They define a new task, Open-Vocabulary Camouflaged Object Segmentation (OVCOS), and release OVCamo: 11,483 hand-selected images with fine masks over 75 relabeled, semantically consistent classes. The split uses 14 seen classes for training and 61 unseen for testing (7713/3770 images), with dataset attributes (e.g., object concentration, color ratio, size) analyzed to capture camouflage difficulty. They adapt evaluation to jointly assess classification and segmentation (e.g., cSm, cFωβ, cMAE, cIoU)."},{"problem":"CLIP-based open-vocabulary segmentation struggles on camouflaged objects because appearance cues alone are weak; models need stronger class-semantic guidance and structural cues within an efficient, single-stage pipeline.","method":"They propose OVCoser, a single-stage, CLIP-driven encoder–decoder baseline with frozen CLIP text and visual encoders. A Semantic Guidance (SG) module injects normalized text embeddings into attention (SGA) to spatially emphasize class-relevant features, while a Structure Enhancement (SE) module adds auxiliary edge and depth branches whose stem features modulate visual features via attention (SEA). An iterative refinement loop feeds back a correlation matrix between visual/text embeddings (M_cor) and an object-aware representation from the previous mask (f_obj) to reweight attention (top-down). Edge/depth are used only as training-time supervision; inference needs only RGB. Final class assignment uses masked average pooling over high-level features and similarity to text embeddings, yielding strong gains on OVCamo with low overhead (<2% trainable params, ~0.2T FLOPs)."},{"problem":"Generic CLIP prompts provide suboptimal semantic context for camouflaged objects, limiting the effectiveness of text-guided segmentation.","method":"They design CamoPrompts, a set of camouflage-aware textual templates (e.g., “A photo of the <class> camouflaged to blend in with its surroundings.”) and average their embeddings per class. On OVCamo, masked-CLIP classification accuracy improves to 0.704 versus typical generic templates (~0.686–0.700), and analysis shows these templates reduce the Hausdorff distance between seen and unseen class embeddings, indicating better transfer of semantic priors."}]}
